Alembic migrations
==================

Schema changes land here as versioned revisions. Never edit the database by
hand — write a revision instead.

Commands (run from `backend/`, with `.env` populated)
-----------------------------------------------------

    alembic current                        # show the DB's current revision
    alembic history                        # list all revisions
    alembic upgrade head                   # apply all pending migrations
    alembic upgrade +1                     # apply one
    alembic downgrade -1                   # roll back one
    alembic revision -m "add foo column"   # new empty revision (hand-write the upgrade)
    alembic revision --autogenerate -m "…" # new revision diffed from the ORM models

Workflow for a new column / index
---------------------------------

1. Edit the SQLAlchemy model under `src/database/postgres/schemas/`.
2. `alembic revision --autogenerate -m "add X"`.
3. Review the generated file — autogenerate misses some things
   (check constraints, server defaults, renames). Fix up if needed.
4. `alembic upgrade head` locally.
5. Commit the revision file.
6. On deploy, run `alembic upgrade head` before starting the new app version.

Legacy baseline
---------------

The first revision (`812e715ead58`) is empty — it exists only so pre-Alembic
databases can be stamped. `schema.sql` is retained as a reference for the
initial shape but is NOT the source of truth going forward.

If you spin up a fresh dev database, you currently still bootstrap via
schema.sql; a future revision should replace that by generating the baseline
from ORM metadata. Until then, after creating a fresh DB run:

    alembic stamp head
